The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Corporate Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Corporate Briefs
                              
	 Financial services firm Magma Shrachi has posted a 17.1 per cent growth in its operating profit at Rs 29.25 crore for the June quarter of 2008-09 compared with Rs 24.98 crore in the corresponding period a year ago. The total asset base of the company rose to Rs 8,005.4 crore for the reporting period from Rs 6,088.30 crore a year ago. Net revenues of the company grew 58.4 per cent to Rs 1,38.51 crore from Rs 87.42 crore in the previous year.                             
	 Central Coalfields Ltd (CCL) has paid dividend on its equity share to Coal India Ltd (CIL) for the third consecutive year. An amount of Rs 250.23 crore for the year ending 2007-08 was presented by CCL chairman and managing director R.P Ritolia to the CIL chairman. A production target of 49.00 million tonnes has been fixed for CCL during the year 2008-09.                             
	 Siemens Mobility division (Siemens AG) along with Siemens Ltd has won a baggage handling contract worth Rs 300 crore from Delhi International Airport Ltd for Terminal 3 baggage handling system.                             
	 Sony Ericsson has launched its Cyber-shot phone range, C902 Cyber-shot. The phone, featuring the latest camera technology, is available in two colours and is priced at Rs 20,995.                            
	 HCL Infosystems Ltd has tied up with Echelon Corporation of the US to bring Echelons advanced metering systems to India. The tie-up will strengthen HCLs position as a system integrator in the field of power.                             
	 Shree Cement has despatched 6.09 lakh tonnes in June 2008. This represents a growth of 27.46 per cent over the corresponding period of the previous year in which it despatched 4.77 lakh tonnes.                             
	 KPIT Cummins Infosystems Ltd has taken over substantial part of the mechanical design services business of Harita TVS Technologies, known as TVS-E Technologies Ltd in India.                             
	 RiskTech, a Hexaware subsidiary, has won three new consulting and implementation contracts in the UK and West Asia.                            
	 Levis has made its foray into footwear and accessories by introducing a comfortable range of canvas flip flops meant for the summer. The Levis flip flops are available in beige and black and priced at Rs 740.                            
	 Titan will foray into the eyewear segment with the launch of the companys latest chain, Titan Eye Plus, which will be the companys third major line of consumer business after watches and jewellery.                                                                                                                  ADVERTISEMENT                   
